The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Sunday, September 19, 2004 

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, Sept. 18: The state government will host a five-day conference from October 8 to discuss the code of conduct for legislators in Assemblies.

 Nearly 400 delegates, including Speakers, deputy Speakers, their secretaries and other officials will attend. Lok Sabha Speaker Somnath Chatterjee will also be present.

 Siliguri: Sub-divisional judicial magistrate Shobhan Mukherjee has remanded B.D. Singh in judicial custody for 14 days. Siliguri police arrested Singh late on Friday night and seized a nine-mm pistol from him. 

 Singh and his associates are believed to have been planning subversive activities in the town ahead of the Siliguri Municipal Corporation elections. 

 Calcutta: Rita Bahuguna, president of All India Mahila Congress, has asked members of the women?s cell to step up a movement against the ?reign of terror? unleashed by the ruling CPM in Bengal.

 She said the Pradesh Mahila Congress would prepare a charter of demands and submit it to Bengal chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee.

 Karimpur (Nadia): Two youths drowned when a country boat capsized in the Bhairav river at Karimpur near Krishnanagar, about 180 km from Calcutta on Friday night. 

 Police said the victims, identified as Ananda Sarkar (22) and Sambhu Dhar (25), were farmers. The bodies have been sent for post mortem.

 Suri (Birbhum): A nurse attached to the Suri Sadar hospital was dismissed on charges of submitting forged certificates of her secondary school examination, held in 2001. 

 Superintendent of police Akhil Roy said Namita Mondal, who joined the hospital nearly a month ago as a trainee nurse, was arrested on Friday from her nursing quarters following a complaint from hospital authorities.




